{"title_page": "Noisy Outlaws", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=January 2010}}\n{{cleanup|date=November 2010}}\n}}\n\n{{italic title}}\n'''''Noisy Outlaws, Unfriendly Blobs, and Some Other Things That Aren't as Scary, Maybe, Depending on How You Feel About Lost Lands, Stray Cellphones, Creatures from the Sky, Parents Who Disappear in Peru, a Man Named Lars Farf, and One Other Story We Couldn't Quite Finish, So Maybe You Could Help Us Out''''', commonly shortened to the first two words, is a collection of short and long stories by noted authors such as [[Nick Hornby]], [[Neil Gaiman]], [[Jon Scieszka]] and others. The collection of short stories was published in 2005 by [[McSweeney's Books]]. The inside of the dust jacket cover of the book contains a half-page story, penned by [[Lemony Snicket]], left unfinished as a part of a contest for readers.<ref>Hamilton, Denise (December 18, 2005). \"[http://articles.latimes.com/2005/dec/18/books/bk-hamilton18 All this, and Lemony Snicket too]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Retrieved April 20, 2013.</ref>\n\n== Contents ==\nThe book contains ten stories and one feature presented in comic book style.\n\nThe stories are not particularly intended for children, though the tone of the majority of stories suggests this. Instead, the stories focus on the apparent (and sometimes exaggerated) weirdness of the world with a childlike innocence.\n\n==Stories==\nThe series starts with \"Small Country\", a short story about a \"six or seven year old\" reluctant football player who has just discovered how small his country really is.\n\n\"Lars Farf, excessively fearful father and husband\" deals with the [[paranoia]] that cripples a father who cares a bit too much about the safety of his family.\n\n\"Monster\" is the horror story in the ensemble that asks some deep questions in the guise of a camp fire tale.\n\n\"The contests at Cowlick\" is an old fashioned western that has more in common with Aesop's fables than the gunslingers of past.\n\n\"Each sold separately\" is a short story that is written in the form of a conversation between a boy and a girl entirely in the form of catchphrases from the advertising world.\n\nIn \"Seymour's last wish\", little Seymour gets a chance to fulfill his wishes. He also has an ogre for a mother, who loves kittens more than she loves him.\n\n\"Grimble\" is a long story about a kid whose parents leave for Peru without notifying him first or telling him why. All they leave is notes, through which Grimble has to survive till they return.\n\n\"Spoony-E and Spandy E\" is an illustrated comic book featuring two \"War buddies\" united against the imminent attack of the \"purple horde\".\n\n\"Sunbird\" is about a club (the Epicureans) who intend to eat all the edible and inedible dishes in the world, including imaginary animals, in order to document all the tastes.\n\n\"The Aces phone\" is about a lost phone found in a park by a boy.\n\n\"The Sixth Borough\" is the final story of the collection, about the sixth [[borough of New York City]] (in reality there are only five) and what happened to it.\n\n==References==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Fiction anthologies]]\n[[Category:2005 books]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=January 2010}}\n{{cleanup|date=November 2010}}\n}}\n\n{{italic title}}\n'''''Noisy Outlaws, Unfriendly Blobs, and Some Other Things That Aren't as Scary, Maybe, Depending on How You Feel About Lost Lands, Stray Cellphones, Creatures from the Sky, Parents Who Disappear in Peru, a Man Named Lars Farf, and One Other Story We Couldn't Quite Finish, So Maybe You Could Help Us Out''''', commonly shortened to the first two words, is a collection of short and long stories by noted authors such as [[Nick Hornby]], [[Neil Gaiman]], [[Jon Scieszka]] and others. The collection of short stories was published in 2005 by [[McSweeney's Books]]. The inside of the dust jacket cover of the book contains a half-page story, penned by [[Lemony Snicket]], left unfinished as a part of a contest for readers.<ref>Hamilton, Denise (December 18, 2005). \"[http://articles.latimes.com/2005/dec/18/books/bk-hamilton18 All this, and Lemony Snicket too]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Retrieved April 20, 2013.</ref>\n\n== Contents ==\nThe book contains ten stories and one feature presented in comic book style.\n\nThe stories are not particularly intended for children, though the tone of the majority of stories suggests this. Instead, the stories focus on the apparent (and sometimes exaggerated) weirdness of the world with a childlike innocence.\n\n==Stories==\nThe series starts with \"Small Country\", a short story about a \"six or seven year old\" reluctant football player who has just discovered how small his country really is.\n\n\"Lars Farf, excessively fearful father and husband\" deals with the [[paranoia]] that cripples a father who cares a bit too much about the safety of his family.\n\n\"Monster\" is the horror story in the ensemble that asks some deep questions in the guise of a camp fire tale.\n\n\"The contests at Cowlick\" is an old fashioned western that has more in common with Aesop's fables than the gunslingers of past.\n\n\"Each sold separately\" is a short story that is written in the form of a conversation between a boy and a girl entirely in the form of catchphrases from the advertising world.\n\nIn \"Seymour's last wish\", little Seymour gets a chance to fulfill his wishes. He also has an ogre for a mother, who loves kittens more than she loves him.\n\n\"Grimble\" is a long story about a kid whose parents leave for Peru without notifying him first or telling him why. All they leave is notes, through which Grimble has to survive till they return.\n\n\"Spoony-E and Spandy E\" is an illustrated comic book featuring two \"War buddies\" united against the imminent attack of the \"purple horde\".\n\n\"Sunbird\" is about a club (the Epicureans) who intend to eat all the edible and inedible dishes in the world, including imaginary animals, in order to document all the tastes.\n\n\"The Aces phone\" is about a lost phone found in a park by a boy.\n\n\"The Sixth Borough\" is the final story of the collection, about the sixth borough of New York, (there are only five) and what happened to it.\n\n==References==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Fiction anthologies]]\n[[Category:2005 books]]\n", "name_user": "BenbowInn", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStories", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noisy_Outlaws"}
{"title_page": "MLS Cup 2000", "text_new": "{{short description|2000 edition of the MLS Cup}}\n{{Refimprove|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox football match\n|title = MLS Cup 2000\n|event = [[MLS Cup]]\n|image = MLSCup2000.png\n|image_size = 200\n|team1 = [[Kansas City Wizards]]\n|team1score = 1\n|team2 = [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]]\n|team2score = 0\n|date=October 15, 2000\n|stadium = [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium]]\n|city = [[Washington, D.C.]], US\n|man_of_the_match1a=[[Tony Meola]]<br />(Kansas City Wizards)\n|weather = Sunny, {{convert|77|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}\n|attendance = 39,159\n|previous = [[MLS Cup 1999|1999]]\n|next = [[MLS Cup 2001|2001]]\n}}\n\n'''MLS Cup 2000''' was the fifth edition of the [[MLS Cup]], the championship match of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), which took place on October 15, 2000, at [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] It was contested by the [[Kansas City Wizards]] and [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] to decide the champion of the [[2000 Major League Soccer season|2000 MLS season]]. Kansas City became the first [[Western Conference (MLS)|Western Conference]] team to win the MLS Cup, with the lone goal of the match scored in the 11th minute by [[Miklos Molnar]]. It was also the first MLS Cup to not feature a team from the [[Eastern Conference (MLS)|Eastern Conference]] club, due to the three-division system used from 2000 to 2001.\n\nThe match was watched by 39,159 spectators and broadcast nationally on [[ESPN on ABC|ABC]] with commentary by [[Jack Edwards (sportscaster)|Jack Edwards]] and [[Ty Keough]].\n\n==Venue==\n[[File:Rfkstadium.png|thumbnail|left|[[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium]] hosted the MLS Cup final for the second time.]]\n\n[[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium]] in Washington, D.C., the home of [[D.C. United]], was chosen to host MLS Cup 2000. It previously hosted [[MLS Cup 1997]], in which the hosts won their second league championship, as well as international competitions like the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]] and [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1996 Olympics men's soccer tournament]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 20, 2017 |title=American soccer made its home at aging, funky RFK Stadium |page= |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2017/10/19/soccer-at-rfk-stadium-its-dirty-and-disgusting-and-ugly-but-its-ours/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref> The 2000 final was the first MLS final to not have D.C. United competing in it,{{cn|date=December 2019}} as the team failed to qualify for the playoffs.<ref>{{cite news |date=September 14, 2000 |title=The Road to M.L.S. Cup \u00b400 |page= |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/09/14/sports/the-road-to-mls-cup-acute00.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=December 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of the match in October 2000, seating capacity of the stadium was 56,454 spectators. RFK Stadium was officially announced as the host on February 23, 2000, beating out the favored bid from [[Raymond James Stadium]] in [[Tampa, Florida]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Page |first=Rodney |date=October 7, 1999 |title=Tampa Bay closes in on hosting MLS Cup |page=C10 |work=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34664356/tampa_bay_closes_in_on_hosting_mls_cup/ |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=August 7, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> which was complicated by a scheduling conflict with a college football team.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=February 24, 2000 |title=RFK to Host Its Second MLS Title Game |page=D7 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/2000/02/24/rfk-to-host-its-second-mls-title-game/c8150890-6349-4257-8937-2fc35e4c2ce0/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Ward |first=Bill |date=February 16, 2000 |title=MLS Cup won't be in Tampa |page=C1 |work=[[The Tampa Tribune]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34664556/mls_cup_wont_be_in_tampa/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=August 7, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n==Road to the final==\n\n===Summary of results===\n:''Note: In all results below, the score of the finalist is given first (H: home; A: away). Playoffs were in [[best of three|best-of-three]] format requiring five points to advance and [[sudden death (sport)|sudden death]] extra time as a tiebreaker.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=4|[[Kansas City Wizards]]\n!Round\n!colspan=4|[[Chicago Fire SC|Chicago Fire]]\n|-\n|colspan=4 valign=top align=center|1st place in [[2000 Major League Soccer season#Western Division|Western Division]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|D|Draws}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#BBF1BD;\"\n|'''1'''||align=left|'''[[Kansas City Wizards]]''' ([[Supporters' Shield|SS]])\n|'''32'''||'''16'''||'''7'''||'''9'''||'''57'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|2||align=left|[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]||32||14||10||8||'''50'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Colorado Rapids]]||32||13||15||4||'''43'''\n|-\n|4||align=left|[[San Jose Earthquakes]]||32||7||17||8||'''29'''\n|}\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/2000 MLS]}}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|[[2000 Major League Soccer season|Regular season]]\n|colspan=4 valign=top|1st place in [[2000 Major League Soccer season#Central Division|Central Division]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|D|Draws}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|'''1'''||align=left|'''[[Chicago Fire SC|Chicago Fire]]'''\n|'''32'''||'''17'''||'''9'''||'''6'''||'''57'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|2||align=left|[[Tampa Bay Mutiny]]||32||16||12||4||'''52'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Dallas Burn]]||32||14||14||4||'''46'''\n|-\n|4||align=left|[[Columbus Crew]]||32||11||16||5||'''38'''\n|}\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/2000 MLS]}}\n|- style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent<br />({{tooltip|Pts.|Points}})\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|3rd leg\n|[[2000 MLS Cup Playoffs|MLS Cup Playoffs]]\n|Opponent<br />({{tooltip|Pts.|Points}})\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|3rd leg\n|-\n|align=left|[[Colorado Rapids]] (7\u20131)\n|1\u20130 (H)\n|0\u20130 (A)\n|3\u20132 (H)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Quarterfinals\n|align=left|[[New England Revolution]] (6\u20133)\n|2\u20131 (H)\n|1\u20132 (A)\n|6\u20130 (H)\n|-\n|align=left|[[Los Angeles Galaxy]] (4\u20134) (1\u20130 [[Sudden death (sport)|SDET]])\n|0\u20130 (H)\n|1\u20132 ([[Sudden death (sport)|ASDET]]) (A)\n|1\u20130 ([[Sudden death (sport)|SDET]]) (H)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Semifinals\n|align=left|[[MetroStars]] (6\u20133)\n|3\u20130 (H)\n|0\u20132 (A)\n|3\u20132 (H)\n|}\n\n==Match==\n===Overview===\nThe match began with Chicago on the offensive early, with Ante Razov and Hristo Stoitchkov creating several attempts within the first ten minutes.\nIn the 11th minute, however, Wizards midfielder [[Chris Klein (soccer)|Chris Klein]] stole the ball from Chicago's [[Diego Guti\u00e9rrez (soccer)|Diego Guti\u00e9rrez]] near midfield and stormed down the touch line. Klein's cross from the right wing made contact with Fire midfielder [[Jesse Marsch]] who failed to clear the ball, allowing [[Miklos Molnar]] to make light contact and roll the ball past keeper [[Zach Thornton]] for the only goal of the match. The Fire responded by using its attacking forces to find an equalizer, but failed to break the Wizards defense and goalkeeper [[Tony Meola]], who made ten saves in the final. Meola earned his 5th shutout of the playoffs in addition to 16 clean sheets to his name from the regular season.\n\n===Details===\n{{football box\n|date=October 15, 2000\n|time=15:30 [[Eastern Daylight Time|EST]]\n|team1=[[Kansas City Wizards]]\n|score=1\u20130\n|report=[https://www.mlssoccer.com/history/mls-cup/2000 Report]\n|team2=[[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]]\n|goals1=[[Miklos Molnar|Molnar]] {{goal|11}}\n|goals2=\n|stadium=[[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium]], Washington, D.C.\n|attendance=39,159\n|referee=[[Paul Tamberino]] ([[United States Soccer Federation|United States]])\n}}\n\n{| width=92% |\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = _adidasstripeswhite\n | pattern_b  = _adidaswhite\n | pattern_ra = _adidasstripeswhite\n | pattern_sh = _adidaswhite\n | pattern_so =\n | leftarm    = 0080FF\n | body       = 0080FF\n | rightarm   = 0080FF\n | shorts     = 0080FF\n | socks      = 0080FF\n | title      =\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la =\n | pattern_b  = _horizontalonwhite\n | pattern_ra =\n | pattern_sh =\n | pattern_so =\n | leftarm    = FFFFFF\n | body       = 000050\n | rightarm   = FFFFFF\n | shorts     = FFFFFF\n | socks      = FFFFFF\n | title      =\n}}\n|}\n{| style=\"width:100%\"\n|-\n|style=\"vertical-align:top; width:40%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Tony Meola]] || {{yel|76}}\n|-\n|RB ||'''3''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Nick Garcia]] || {{yel|58}}\n|-\n|CB ||'''6''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Peter Vermes]]\n|-\n|LB ||'''4''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Brandon Prideaux]]\n|-\n|RM ||'''17'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Chris Klein (soccer)|Chris Klein]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]]) || {{suboff|88}}\n|-\n|CM ||'''15''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Kerry Zavagnin]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''2'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Matt McKeon]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Preki]] || {{suboff|