{"title_page": "2012 Norwegian Air Force C-130 crash", "text_new": "{{short description|2012 air disaster}}\n{{Infobox aircraft occurrence\n| image           = Royal Norwegian Air Force Lockheed C-130J Hercules Lofting.jpg\n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = A Royal Norwegian Air Force C-130 similar to the one involved\n| occurrence_type = Accident\n| date            = {{start date|2012|03|15|df=y}}\n| summary         = [[Controlled flight into terrain]] due to [[pilot error]] and [[Air traffic control|ATC]] error\n| site            = [[Mount Kebnekaise]], [[Lapland (Sweden)|Lapland]], Sweden\n| coordinates     = {{Coord|67|54|N|18|31|E|type:event|display = inline,title}}\n| aircraft_type   = [[Lockheed Martin C-130J Super Hercules]]\n| aircraft_name   = ''Siv''\n| operator        = [[Royal Norwegian Air Force]]\n| callsign        = HAZE 01\n| tail_number     = 5630\n| origin          = [[Harstad/Narvik Airport]], [[Harstad]], Norway\n| stopover        = \n| destination     = [[Kiruna Airport]], [[Kiruna]], Sweden\n| occupants       = 5\n| crew            = 5\n| fatalities      = 5\n| survivors       = 0\n}}\n\nOn 15 March 2012, a [[C-130J Super Hercules]] military transport aircraft of the [[Royal Norwegian Air Force]] ({{lang-no|Luftforsvaret}}) crashed into the western face of [[Mount Kebnekaise]] near [[Kiruna]], Sweden.<ref name=\"Fly sporl\u00f8st borte\"/><ref name=\"siste tegn\">{{cite news |title=Her er siste tegn fra flyet |author=Atle J\u00f8rstad |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079153 |newspaper=[[Verdens Gang]] |language=Norwegian |date=15 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |display-authors=etal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316183216/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079153 |archive-date=16 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> All five people on board were killed.<ref name=Local>{{cite news |title=Body parts found at Hercules crash site |url=http://www.thelocal.se/39734/20120317/ |newspaper=[[The Local]] |date=17 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319233815/http://www.thelocal.se/39734/20120317 |archive-date=19 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nSwedish air traffic control had given the crew a clearance that placed them outside controlled airspace and below the altitude of the surrounding terrain, a circumstance that went unnoticed to the crew. Contributing to the accident was the pilots' decision to configure the aircraft in tactical mode, despite not conducting a tactical operation. In this mode, the aircraft's [[terrain warning system]] was inhibited, meaning the pilots were not alerted to the risk of collision with terrain.\n\n== Accident ==\n{{Location map\n |Sweden Norrbotten\n |label=Kebnekaise mountain range\n |label_size=80\n |width=\n |mark=Cercle rouge 100%.svg\n |marksize=30\n |lat_deg=67|lat_min=53 |lat_dir=N\n |lon_deg=18|lon_min=33|lon_dir=E\n |caption= Location in northern Sweden\n |position=right\n |float=right\n}}\nThe plane left [[Evenes Airport]] at 13:40 and was scheduled to arrive at [[Kiruna Airport]] at 14:30.<ref name=\"Fly sporl\u00f8st borte\">{{cite news |title=Fly sporl\u00f8st borte \u2013 fem nordmenn savnet |author=Rune Thomas Ege |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079136 |newspaper=[[Verdens Gang]] |language=Norwegian |date=15 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |display-authors=etal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317054150/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079136 |archive-date=17 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The aircraft was participating in the \"[[Cold Response]]\" military exercise, which also involved forces from Germany, Britain, Canada, Denmark, France, the Netherlands, Sweden and the United States. The aircraft appeared to have flown straight onto the edge<ref name=edge>[http://www.tu.no/motor/2012/03/19/gikk-nesten-klar-av-fjellryggen \"Went almost clear of the mountainside\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421180946/http://www.tu.no/motor/2012/03/19/gikk-nesten-klar-av-fjellryggen |date=21 April 2012 }}, ''[[Teknisk Ukeblad]]'' 19 March 2012. Retrieved: 7 August 2012.</ref> of the western wall of [[Kebnekaise]], Sweden's highest mountain.<ref name=\"siste tegn\"/><ref name=\"dayton\">{{cite news|title=Body parts found at plane crash site in Sweden |author=Karl Ritter |url=http://www.daytondailynews.com/news/nation-world-news/body-parts-found-at-plane-crash-site-in-sweden-1345382.html |newspaper=[[Dayton Daily News]] |date=17 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> According to a police spokesperson, the aircraft probably exploded after crashing, setting off an [[avalanche]]. [[Cadaver|Human remains]] were found in the avalanche area.<ref name=Local/>\n\nThe radar plots show the aircraft maintained a straight course over the last 50&nbsp;km of the flight until impact, in line with the planned route. The plots did not indicate tactical low-level flying, although that was an optional plan for part of the route if weather conditions allowed. Just prior to the crash, Swedish air traffic controllers at Kiruna cleared the Hercules to descend to 7,000 feet (2,134 meters). This altitude is just 20 meters above the height of the top of the Kebnekaise mountain.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10053225 |title=Archived copy |access-date=11 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512195159/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10053225 |archive-date=12 May 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The altitudes for the continuous radar plots remained in the possession of the accident investigation board and were not released.<ref>{{cite news |title=Flyet holdt planlagt kurs da det styrtet |author1=Andreas Budalen |author2=Gerd Elise Martinsen |url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.8041231 |publisher=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation|NRK]] |language=Norwegian |date=19 March 2012 |accessdate=26 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321182704/http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.8041231 |archive-date=21 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n== Aircraft ==\nThe aircraft involved was a [[Lockheed Martin C-130J Super Hercules]] as 5630 (USAF serial no: 10-5630, c/n: 382-5630), a four-engine turboprop military transport aircraft. It was the last of four such planes acquired by the Norwegian military between 2008 and 2010 and was named ''[[Sif|Siv]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tredje ulykken med det nye Hercules-flyet |author=Paal Wergeland |author2=Heidi Magnussen |url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/norge/1.8038397 |publisher=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation|NRK]] |language=Norwegian |date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317120437/http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/norge/1.8038397 |archive-date=17 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nThe commander, 42-year-old St\u00e5le Garberg, had 6229 flight hours, while the first officer, 46-year-old Truls Audun \u00d8rpen, had 3286 flight hours. Both were considered to be experienced airmen.\n\n== Victims ==\nA total of five people (a crew of four plus an extra officer) were aboard the aircraft when it crashed. All of them were Royal Norwegian Air Force officers and \"among the most experienced\" in the Norwegian military, according to the head of the Norwegian Armed Forces.<ref name=local2>{{cite news |title=Plane 'smashed' into Sweden's tallest peak |url=http://www.thelocal.se/39724/20120317/ |newspaper=[[The Local]] |date=17 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319211311/http://www.thelocal.se/39724/20120317 |archive-date=19 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The names of the missing were released by the military on 16 March 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Navnene p\u00e5 de savnede er offentliggjort |author=Kristine Hellem Aanstad |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079149 |newspaper=[[Verdens Gang]] |language=Norwegian |date=15 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |display-authors=etal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316181050/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079149 |archive-date=16 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Dette er mannskapet som er savnet etter flystyrten |author=Kristian Ervik |url=http://www.tv2.no/nyheter/innenriks/dette-er-mannskapet-som-er-savnet-etter-flystyrten-3734764.html |publisher=[[TV 2 (Norway)|TV 2]] |language=Norwegian |date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319005338/http://www.tv2.no/nyheter/innenriks/dette-er-mannskapet-som-er-savnet-etter-flystyrten-3734764.html |archive-date=19 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n* 13:40 The Norwegian Hercules plane takes off from Evenes in northern Norway, destination Kiruna, Sweden.\n* 14:43 Radio contact with the plane.\n* 14:5x The Kiruna Airport control tower had radio contact with the plane shortly before the last radar observation. The exact time and details or transcripts of this conversation were not published during the investigation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hercules-flyets siste samtale hemmeligstemplet: Snakket med flyt\u00e5rn like f\u00f8r de krasjet |author1=Hilda Nyfl\u00f8t |author2=Sigrid Moe |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2012/03/20/nyheter/kebnekaise/hercules-ulykken/letemannskap/20760440/ |newspaper=[[Dagbladet]] |language=Norwegian |date=20 March 2012 |accessdate=26 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322190315/http://www.dagbladet.no/2012/03/20/nyheter/kebnekaise/hercules-ulykken/letemannskap/20760440/ |archive-date=22 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n* 14:56 Last radar observation of the aircraft just west of the 6950 feet high Kebnekaise mountain peaks, by civilian radar (Kiruna, distance {{convert|75|km|mi}}) at 7200 feet. Military radar at S\u00f8rreisa (distance {{convert|130|km|mi}}) registered last altitude at 7600 feet at about the same time.<ref>{{cite news |title=Varmesignatur var ikke savnet fly: Redningsleder: 'Urolig for at de kan ha kommet n\u00e6r fjelltopp' |author=Audun Beyer-Olsen |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079158 |newspaper=[[Verdens Gang]] |language=Norwegian |date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=26 March 2012 |display-authors=etal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318153229/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079158 |archive-date=18 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nFollowing the accident, a [[Search and rescue|search effort]] led by Swedish rescue service was launched, but was hampered by snow, wind and cloud cover, impeding helicopter reconnaissance. Around 4&nbsp;pm [[Central European Time]] on 16 March, a Norwegian [[P-3 Orion]] aircraft participating in the search spotted an orange or red object on the ground in the Kebnekaise mountain range.<ref>{{cite news |title=Overv\u00e5kingsfly har gjort funn ved Kebnekaise |author=Kristian Ervik |url=http://www.tv2.no/nyheter/innenriks/overvaakingsfly-har-gjort-funn-ved-kebnekaise-3735357.html |publisher=[[TV 2 (Norway)|TV 2]] |language=Norwegian |date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318042618/http://www.tv2.no/nyheter/innenriks/overvaakingsfly-har-gjort-funn-ved-kebnekaise-3735357.html |archive-date=18 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Kan ha funnet deler av ulykkesflyet |author=Rune Thomas Ege |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079240 |newspaper=[[Verdens Gang]] |language=Norwegian |date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |display-authors=etal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317163918/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079240 |archive-date=17 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Danish helicopters attempted to locate and identify the object, but due to the weather conditions, the search was called off before any finds were made. Later thousands of pieces of wreckage and debris were located at the site identified by the Orion aircraft.<ref>{{cite news |title=Har funnet et jakkeerme |author=Johannes B\u00f8rstad |url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.8038941 |publisher=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation|NRK]] |language=Norwegian |date=17 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |display-authors=etal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318015103/http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.8038941 |archive-date=18 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Some of the parts showed burn marks and smelled of [[kerosene]]. Footage recorded by the Orion plane showed what appeared to be soot and ashes spread over the side of the mountain.<ref>{{cite news |title=Her krasjet Hercules-flyet |url=http://www.tv2.no/play/nyheter/utenriks/her-krasjet-hercules-flyet-601588.html |publisher=[[TV 2 (Norway)|TV 2]] |format=video |language=Norwegian |date=17 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322132940/http://www.tv2.no/play/nyheter/utenriks/her-krasjet-hercules-flyet-601588.html |archive-date=22 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Through the use of [[Search and rescue dog|search dogs]], human remains were discovered and relocated for [[DNA profiling|DNA testing]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Svensk politi: Har funnet kroppsdeler |author=Vilde Helljesen |url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/verden/1.8039516 |publisher=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation|NRK]] |language=Norwegian |date=17 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318015127/http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/verden/1.8039516 |archive-date=18 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and subsequently on 17 March the search for survivors was called off since it was believed that all five people on board had been killed and the aircraft destroyed.<ref name=\"dayton\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Norwegian Hercules plane missing in Sweden |url=http://www.thelocal.se/39694/20120315/ |newspaper=[[The Local]] |date=15 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316232533/http://www.thelocal.se/39694/20120315/ |archivedate=16 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Norwegian aeroplane missing in Sweden |url=http://www.skynews.com.au/world/article.aspx?id=729418&vId= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303211824/http://www.skynews.com.au/world/article.aspx?id=729418&vId= |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 March 2016 |publisher=[[Sky News Australia]] |date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012}}</ref> Efforts were refocused on an [[Accident analysis|accident investigation]].\n\n== Investigation ==\nThe ongoing investigation is headed by the [[Swedish Accident Investigation Board|Swedish Accident Investigation Authority]] with participation of the [[Accident Investigation Board Norway|Norwegian Accident Investigation Board]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Vi kommer til \u00e5 finne svaret |author=Kjell Mikalsen & Andreas Budalen |url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.8046493 |publisher=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation|NRK]] |language=Norwegian |date=22 March 2012 |accessdate=22 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322203730/http://nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.8046493 |archive-date=22 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The aircraft is considered to have been completely destroyed by the impact and the following explosion, and on 22 March work began on moving debris from the temporary investigative base in [[Nikkaluokta]] near the crash site to an aircraft hangar at [[Kiruna Airport]], but efforts were still being hampered by adverse weather and the discovery of further cracks in the glacier on which the debris is located.<ref>{{cite news |title=Utredningsarbetet i Kebnekaisemassivet |url=http://www.havkom.se/news.asp?newsID=601 |publisher=Swedish Accident Investigation Authority |date=22 March 2012 |accessdate=25 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223110607/http://www.havkom.se/news.asp?newsID=601 |archive-date=23 February 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name=clean>[http://www.tu.no/miljo/2012/08/06/telemark-bataljon-rydder-pa-kebnekaise \"Telemark Battalion cleans on Kebnekaise\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120810011624/http://www.tu.no/miljo/2012/08/06/telemark-bataljon-rydder-pa-kebnekaise |date=10 August 2012 }}, ''[[Teknisk Ukeblad]]'' 6 August 2012. Retrieved: 7 August 2012.</ref> In August 2012 both the [[cockpit voice recorder]] and the [[flight data recorder]] were found<ref name=cvr>[http://www.tu.no/motor/2012/08/05/fant-taleregistrator-ved-kebnekaise \"Voice recorder found\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120807040852/http://www.tu.no/motor/2012/08/05/fant-taleregistrator-ved-kebnekaise |date=7 August 2012 }}, ''[[Teknisk Ukeblad]]'' 5 August 2012. Retrieved: 7 August 2012.</ref><ref name=fdr>[http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/uriks/Ferdskriveren-fra-Hercules-flyet-funnet-6963823.html \"Flight data recorder found\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029202344/http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/uriks/Ferdskriveren-fra-Hercules-flyet-funnet-6963823.html |date=29 October 2013 }}, ''[[Aftenposten]]'' 12 August 2012. Retrieved: 12 August 2012.</ref> and flown to the United Kingdom where experts at the [[Air Accidents Investigation Branch]] are aiding local authorities in salvaging data from the two recorders<ref>{{cite web|last=Marfelt|first=Birgitte|title=Britiske specialister lirker sandheden om norsk flystyrt ud af boksene|url=http://ing.dk/artikel/131231-britiske-specialister-lirker-sandheden-om-norsk-flystyrt-ud-af-boksene|publisher=Ingeni\u00f8ren|access-date=16 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017071514/http://ing.dk/artikel/131231-britiske-specialister-lirker-sandheden-om-norsk-flystyrt-ud-af-boksene|archive-date=17 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> as Sweden does not have the expertise to handle flight recorders as damaged as the ones found in the wreckage. By 3 October 2012 NRK reported that data from the flight recorders had been successfully downloaded, and preliminary results have indicated that the terrain warning system was set for landing, so no warning was given before impact.<ref>{{cite web|last=HOLMSTR\u00d6M|first=MIKAEL|title=Ingen varning f\u00f6re kraschen|url=http://www.svd.se/nyheter/inrikes/ingen-varning-fore-kraschen_7750628.svd|publisher=[[Svenska Dagbladet]]|accessdate=13 December 2012|date=12 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121214014656/http://www.svd.se/nyheter/inrikes/ingen-varning-fore-kraschen_7750628.svd|archive-date=14 December 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe accident report was repeatedly delayed,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Budalen|first1=Andreas|last2=Johansen|first2=Adrian Dahl|title=Hercules-rapporten blir utsatt til april|url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.10900354|newspaper=[[NRK]]|date=5 February 2013|access-date=14 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206175515/http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.10900354|archive-date=6 February 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Andersen|first=Barbro|title=Hercules-rapporten kommer f\u00f8rst om noen m\u00e5neder|url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.10937289|newspaper=NRK|date=5 March 2013|access-date=14 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307020534/http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.10937289|archive-date=7 March 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> but was released by the Swedish Accident Investigation Authority (Statens haverikommission) on 22 October 2013<ref>{{cite web|title=RM 2013_02_e.pdf (English Version)|website=havkom.se|date=22 October 2013|url=http://www.havkom.se/virtupload/reports/RM%202013_02_e.pdf|access-date=12 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203010223/http://www.havkom.se/virtupload/reports/RM%202013_02_e.pdf|archive-date=3 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> stating:\n\n{{Quote|quote=The accident was caused by the crew on HAZE 01 not noticing the shortcomings in the clearances issued by the air traffic controllers and to the risks of following these clearances, which resulted in the aircraft coming to leave controlled airspace and be flown at an altitude that was lower than the surrounding terrain}}\n\nIn 2019 it became known that the flight crew did not have maps showing the height of the mountain Kebnekaise. The map they were issued had little or wrong information about the terrain in Sweden, the reason was that the Air Force lacked map data for Sweden. It was an information that did not appear clearly in the accident report, but as an internal investigation by the Air Force, that was started after a former Air Force employee had notified about it in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nrk.no/nordland/kebnekaise-flyet-floy-med-feil-kart-1.14485005|title=Kebnekaise-flyet fl\u00f8y med feil kart (Norwegian)|last=Skj\u00e5stad Lysvold|first=Susanne|date=22 March 2019|work=NRK}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.klassekampen.no/article/20190322/ARTICLE/190329989|title=Gransker ulykken p\u00e5 nytt (Norwegian)|last=Lysberg|first=Magnus|date=22 March 2019|work=Klassekampen|last2=Tallaksen|first2=Simen}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in 2012}}\n{{Portal bar|Aviation|Norway|Sweden}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Norwegian Air Force C-130 crash, 2012}}\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 2012]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents involving controlled flight into terrain]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents caused by pilot error]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents caused by air traffic controller error]]\n[[Category:2012 in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving the Lockheed Hercules]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving Royal Norwegian Air Force aircraft]]\n[[Category:Kebnekaise]]\n[[Category:March 2012 events in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2012 air disaster}}\n{{Infobox aircraft occurrence\n| image           = Royal Norwegian Air Force Lockheed C-130J Hercules Lofting.jpg\n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = A Royal Norwegian Air Force C-130 similar to the one involved\n| occurrence_type = Accident\n| date            = {{start date|2012|03|15|df=y}}\n| summary         = [[Controlled flight into terrain]] due to [[pilot error]] \n| site            = [[Mount Kebnekaise]], [[Lapland (Sweden)|Lapland]], Sweden\n| coordinates     = {{Coord|67|54|N|18|31|E|type:event|display = inline,title}}\n| aircraft_type   = [[Lockheed Martin C-130J Super Hercules]]\n| aircraft_name   = ''Siv''\n| operator        = [[Royal Norwegian Air Force]]\n| callsign        = HAZE 01\n| tail_number     = 5630\n| origin          = [[Harstad/Narvik Airport]], [[Harstad]], Norway\n| stopover        = \n| destination     = [[Kiruna Airport]], [[Kiruna]], Sweden\n| occupants       = 5\n| crew            = 5\n| fatalities      = 5\n| survivors       = 0\n}}\n\nOn 15 March 2012, a [[C-130J Super Hercules]] military transport aircraft of the [[Royal Norwegian Air Force]] ({{lang-no|Luftforsvaret}}) crashed into the western face of [[Mount Kebnekaise]] near [[Kiruna]], Sweden.<ref name=\"Fly sporl\u00f8st borte\"/><ref name=\"siste tegn\">{{cite news |title=Her er siste tegn fra flyet |author=Atle J\u00f8rstad |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079153 |newspaper=[[Verdens Gang]] |language=Norwegian |date=15 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |display-authors=etal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316183216/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079153 |archive-date=16 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> All five people on board were killed.<ref name=Local>{{cite news |title=Body parts found at Hercules crash site |url=http://www.thelocal.se/39734/20120317/ |newspaper=[[The Local]] |date=17 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319233815/http://www.thelocal.se/39734/20120317 |archive-date=19 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nSwedish air traffic control had given the crew a clearance that placed them outside controlled airspace and below the altitude of the surrounding terrain, a circumstance that went unnoticed to the crew. Contributing to the accident was the pilots' decision to configure the aircraft in tactical mode, despite not conducting a tactical operation. In this mode, the aircraft's [[terrain warning system]] was inhibited, meaning the pilots were not alerted to the risk of collision with terrain.\n\n== Accident ==\n{{Location map\n |Sweden Norrbotten\n |label=Kebnekaise mountain range\n |label_size=80\n |width=\n |mark=Cercle rouge 100%.svg\n |marksize=30\n |lat_deg=67|lat_min=53 |lat_dir=N\n |lon_deg=18|lon_min=33|lon_dir=E\n |caption= Location in northern Sweden\n |position=right\n |float=right\n}}\nThe plane left [[Evenes Airport]] at 13:40 and was scheduled to arrive at [[Kiruna Airport]] at 14:30.<ref name=\"Fly sporl\u00f8st borte\">{{cite news |title=Fly sporl\u00f8st borte \u2013 fem nordmenn savnet |author=Rune Thomas Ege |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079136 |newspaper=[[Verdens Gang]] |language=Norwegian |date=15 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |display-authors=etal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317054150/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079136 |archive-date=17 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The aircraft was participating in the \"[[Cold Response]]\" military exercise, which also involved forces from Germany, Britain, Canada, Denmark, France, the Netherlands, Sweden and the United States. The aircraft appeared to have flown straight onto the edge<ref name=edge>[http://www.tu.no/motor/2012/03/19/gikk-nesten-klar-av-fjellryggen \"Went almost clear of the mountainside\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421180946/http://www.tu.no/motor/2012/03/19/gikk-nesten-klar-av-fjellryggen |date=21 April 2012 }}, ''[[Teknisk Ukeblad]]'' 19 March 2012. Retrieved: 7 August 2012.</ref> of the western wall of [[Kebnekaise]], Sweden's highest mountain.<ref name=\"siste tegn\"/><ref name=\"dayton\">{{cite news|title=Body parts found at plane crash site in Sweden |author=Karl Ritter |url=http://www.daytondailynews.com/news/nation-world-news/body-parts-found-at-plane-crash-site-in-sweden-1345382.html |newspaper=[[Dayton Daily News]] |date=17 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> According to a police spokesperson, the aircraft probably exploded after crashing, setting off an [[avalanche]]. [[Cadaver|Human remains]] were found in the avalanche area.<ref name=Local/>\n\nThe radar plots show the aircraft maintained a straight course over the last 50&nbsp;km of the flight until impact, in line with the planned route. The plots did not indicate tactical low-level flying, although that was an optional plan for part of the route if weather conditions allowed. Just prior to the crash, Swedish air traffic controllers at Kiruna cleared the Hercules to descend to 7,000 feet (2,134 meters). This altitude is just 20 meters above the height of the top of the Kebnekaise mountain.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10053225 |title=Archived copy |access-date=11 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512195159/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10053225 |archive-date=12 May 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The altitudes for the continuous radar plots remained in the possession of the accident investigation board and were not released.<ref>{{cite news |title=Flyet holdt planlagt kurs da det styrtet |author1=Andreas Budalen |author2=Gerd Elise Martinsen |url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.8041231 |publisher=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation|NRK]] |language=Norwegian |date=19 March 2012 |accessdate=26 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321182704/http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.8041231 |archive-date=21 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n== Aircraft ==\nThe aircraft involved was a [[Lockheed Martin C-130J Super Hercules]] as 5630 (USAF serial no: 10-5630, c/n: 382-5630), a four-engine turboprop military transport aircraft. It was the last of four such planes acquired by the Norwegian military between 2008 and 2010 and was named ''[[Sif|Siv]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tredje ulykken med det nye Hercules-flyet |author=Paal Wergeland |author2=Heidi Magnussen |url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/norge/1.8038397 |publisher=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation|NRK]] |language=Norwegian |date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317120437/http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/norge/1.8038397 |archive-date=17 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nThe commander, 42-year-old St\u00e5le Garberg, had 6229 flight hours, while the first officer, 46-year-old Truls Audun \u00d8rpen, had 3286 flight hours. Both were considered to be experienced airmen.\n\n== Victims ==\nA total of five people (a crew of four plus an extra officer) were aboard the aircraft when it crashed. All of them were Royal Norwegian Air Force officers and \"among the most experienced\" in the Norwegian military, according to the head of the Norwegian Armed Forces.<ref name=local2>{{cite news |title=Plane 'smashed' into Sweden's tallest peak |url=http://www.thelocal.se/39724/20120317/ |newspaper=[[The Local]] |date=17 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319211311/http://www.thelocal.se/39724/20120317 |archive-date=19 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The names of the missing were released by the military on 16 March 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Navnene p\u00e5 de savnede er offentliggjort |author=Kristine Hellem Aanstad |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079149 |newspaper=[[Verdens Gang]] |language=Norwegian |date=15 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |display-authors=etal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316181050/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079149 |archive-date=16 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Dette er mannskapet som er savnet etter flystyrten |author=Kristian Ervik |url=http://www.tv2.no/nyheter/innenriks/dette-er-mannskapet-som-er-savnet-etter-flystyrten-3734764.html |publisher=[[TV 2 (Norway)|TV 2]] |language=Norwegian |date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319005338/http://www.tv2.no/nyheter/innenriks/dette-er-mannskapet-som-er-savnet-etter-flystyrten-3734764.html |archive-date=19 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n* 13:40 The Norwegian Hercules plane takes off from Evenes in northern Norway, destination Kiruna, Sweden.\n* 14:43 Radio contact with the plane.\n* 14:5x The Kiruna Airport control tower had radio contact with the plane shortly before the last radar observation. The exact time and details or transcripts of this conversation were not published during the investigation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hercules-flyets siste samtale hemmeligstemplet: Snakket med flyt\u00e5rn like f\u00f8r de krasjet |author1=Hilda Nyfl\u00f8t |author2=Sigrid Moe |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2012/03/20/nyheter/kebnekaise/hercules-ulykken/letemannskap/20760440/ |newspaper=[[Dagbladet]] |language=Norwegian |date=20 March 2012 |accessdate=26 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322190315/http://www.dagbladet.no/2012/03/20/nyheter/kebnekaise/hercules-ulykken/letemannskap/20760440/ |archive-date=22 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n* 14:56 Last radar observation of the aircraft just west of the 6950 feet high Kebnekaise mountain peaks, by civilian radar (Kiruna, distance {{convert|75|km|mi}}) at 7200 feet. Military radar at S\u00f8rreisa (distance {{convert|130|km|mi}}) registered last altitude at 7600 feet at about the same time.<ref>{{cite news |title=Varmesignatur var ikke savnet fly: Redningsleder: 'Urolig for at de kan ha kommet n\u00e6r fjelltopp' |author=Audun Beyer-Olsen |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079158 |newspaper=[[Verdens Gang]] |language=Norwegian |date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=26 March 2012 |display-authors=etal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318153229/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079158 |archive-date=18 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nFollowing the accident, a [[Search and rescue|search effort]] led by Swedish rescue service was launched, but was hampered by snow, wind and cloud cover, impeding helicopter reconnaissance. Around 4&nbsp;pm [[Central European Time]] on 16 March, a Norwegian [[P-3 Orion]] aircraft participating in the search spotted an orange or red object on the ground in the Kebnekaise mountain range.<ref>{{cite news |title=Overv\u00e5kingsfly har gjort funn ved Kebnekaise |author=Kristian Ervik |url=http://www.tv2.no/nyheter/innenriks/overvaakingsfly-har-gjort-funn-ved-kebnekaise-3735357.html |publisher=[[TV 2 (Norway)|TV 2]] |language=Norwegian |date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318042618/http://www.tv2.no/nyheter/innenriks/overvaakingsfly-har-gjort-funn-ved-kebnekaise-3735357.html |archive-date=18 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Kan ha funnet deler av ulykkesflyet |author=Rune Thomas Ege |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079240 |newspaper=[[Verdens Gang]] |language=Norwegian |date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |display-authors=etal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317163918/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10079240 |archive-date=17 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Danish helicopters attempted to locate and identify the object, but due to the weather conditions, the search was called off before any finds were made. Later thousands of pieces of wreckage and debris were located at the site identified by the Orion aircraft.<ref>{{cite news |title=Har funnet et jakkeerme |author=Johannes B\u00f8rstad |url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.8038941 |publisher=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation|NRK]] |language=Norwegian |date=17 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |display-authors=etal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318015103/http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.8038941 |archive-date=18 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Some of the parts showed burn marks and smelled of [[kerosene]]. Footage recorded by the Orion plane showed what appeared to be soot and ashes spread over the side of the mountain.<ref>{{cite news |title=Her krasjet Hercules-flyet |url=http://www.tv2.no/play/nyheter/utenriks/her-krasjet-hercules-flyet-601588.html |publisher=[[TV 2 (Norway)|TV 2]] |format=video |language=Norwegian |date=17 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322132940/http://www.tv2.no/play/nyheter/utenriks/her-krasjet-hercules-flyet-601588.html |archive-date=22 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Through the use of [[Search and rescue dog|search dogs]], human remains were discovered and relocated for [[DNA profiling|DNA testing]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Svensk politi: Har funnet kroppsdeler |author=Vilde Helljesen |url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/verden/1.8039516 |publisher=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation|NRK]] |language=Norwegian |date=17 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318015127/http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/verden/1.8039516 |archive-date=18 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and subsequently on 17 March the search for survivors was called off since it was believed that all five people on board had been killed and the aircraft destroyed.<ref name=\"dayton\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Norwegian Hercules plane missing in Sweden |url=http://www.thelocal.se/39694/20120315/ |newspaper=[[The Local]] |date=15 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316232533/http://www.thelocal.se/39694/20120315/ |archivedate=16 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Norwegian aeroplane missing in Sweden |url=http://www.skynews.com.au/world/article.aspx?id=729418&vId= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303211824/http://www.skynews.com.au/world/article.aspx?id=729418&vId= |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 March 2016 |publisher=[[Sky News Australia]] |date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=17 March 2012}}</ref> Efforts were refocused on an [[Accident analysis|accident investigation]].\n\n== Investigation ==\nThe ongoing investigation is headed by the [[Swedish Accident Investigation Board|Swedish Accident Investigation Authority]] with participation of the [[Accident Investigation Board Norway|Norwegian Accident Investigation Board]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Vi kommer til \u00e5 finne svaret |author=Kjell Mikalsen & Andreas Budalen |url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.8046493 |publisher=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation|NRK]] |language=Norwegian |date=22 March 2012 |accessdate=22 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322203730/http://nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.8046493 |archive-date=22 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The aircraft is considered to have been completely destroyed by the impact and the following explosion, and on 22 March work began on moving debris from the temporary investigative base in [[Nikkaluokta]] near the crash site to an aircraft hangar at [[Kiruna Airport]], but efforts were still being hampered by adverse weather and the discovery of further cracks in the glacier on which the debris is located.<ref>{{cite news |title=Utredningsarbetet i Kebnekaisemassivet |url=http://www.havkom.se/news.asp?newsID=601 |publisher=Swedish Accident Investigation Authority |date=22 March 2012 |accessdate=25 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223110607/http://www.havkom.se/news.asp?newsID=601 |archive-date=23 February 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name=clean>[http://www.tu.no/miljo/2012/08/06/telemark-bataljon-rydder-pa-kebnekaise \"Telemark Battalion cleans on Kebnekaise\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120810011624/http://www.tu.no/miljo/2012/08/06/telemark-bataljon-rydder-pa-kebnekaise |date=10 August 2012 }}, ''[[Teknisk Ukeblad]]'' 6 August 2012. Retrieved: 7 August 2012.</ref> In August 2012 both the [[cockpit voice recorder]] and the [[flight data recorder]] were found<ref name=cvr>[http://www.tu.no/motor/2012/08/05/fant-taleregistrator-ved-kebnekaise \"Voice recorder found\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120807040852/http://www.tu.no/motor/2012/08/05/fant-taleregistrator-ved-kebnekaise |date=7 August 2012 }}, ''[[Teknisk Ukeblad]]'' 5 August 2012. Retrieved: 7 August 2012.</ref><ref name=fdr>[http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/uriks/Ferdskriveren-fra-Hercules-flyet-funnet-6963823.html \"Flight data recorder found\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029202344/http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/uriks/Ferdskriveren-fra-Hercules-flyet-funnet-6963823.html |date=29 October 2013 }}, ''[[Aftenposten]]'' 12 August 2012. Retrieved: 12 August 2012.</ref> and flown to the United Kingdom where experts at the [[Air Accidents Investigation Branch]] are aiding local authorities in salvaging data from the two recorders<ref>{{cite web|last=Marfelt|first=Birgitte|title=Britiske specialister lirker sandheden om norsk flystyrt ud af boksene|url=http://ing.dk/artikel/131231-britiske-specialister-lirker-sandheden-om-norsk-flystyrt-ud-af-boksene|publisher=Ingeni\u00f8ren|access-date=16 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017071514/http://ing.dk/artikel/131231-britiske-specialister-lirker-sandheden-om-norsk-flystyrt-ud-af-boksene|archive-date=17 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> as Sweden does not have the expertise to handle flight recorders as damaged as the ones found in the wreckage. By 3 October 2012 NRK reported that data from the flight recorders had been successfully downloaded, and preliminary results have indicated that the terrain warning system was set for landing, so no warning was given before impact.<ref>{{cite web|last=HOLMSTR\u00d6M|first=MIKAEL|title=Ingen varning f\u00f6re kraschen|url=http://www.svd.se/nyheter/inrikes/ingen-varning-fore-kraschen_7750628.svd|publisher=[[Svenska Dagbladet]]|accessdate=13 December 2012|date=12 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121214014656/http://www.svd.se/nyheter/inrikes/ingen-varning-fore-kraschen_7750628.svd|archive-date=14 December 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe accident report was repeatedly delayed,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Budalen|first1=Andreas|last2=Johansen|first2=Adrian Dahl|title=Hercules-rapporten blir utsatt til april|url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.10900354|newspaper=[[NRK]]|date=5 February 2013|access-date=14 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206175515/http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.10900354|archive-date=6 February 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Andersen|first=Barbro|title=Hercules-rapporten kommer f\u00f8rst om noen m\u00e5neder|url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.10937289|newspaper=NRK|date=5 March 2013|access-date=14 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307020534/http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/nordland/1.10937289|archive-date=7 March 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> but was released by the Swedish Accident Investigation Authority (Statens haverikommission) on 22 October 2013<ref>{{cite web|title=RM 2013_02_e.pdf (English Version)|website=havkom.se|date=22 October 2013|url=http://www.havkom.se/virtupload/reports/RM%202013_02_e.pdf|access-date=12 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203010223/http://www.havkom.se/virtupload/reports/RM%202013_02_e.pdf|archive-date=3 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> stating:\n\n{{Quote|quote=The accident was caused by the crew on HAZE 01 not noticing the shortcomings in the clearances issued by the air traffic controllers and to the risks of following these clearances, which resulted in the aircraft coming to leave controlled airspace and be flown at an altitude that was lower than the surrounding terrain}}\n\nIn 2019 it became known that the flight crew did not have maps showing the height of the mountain Kebnekaise. The map they were issued had little or wrong information about the terrain in Sweden, the reason was that the Air Force lacked map data for Sweden. It was an information that did not appear clearly in the accident report, but as an internal investigation by the Air Force, that was started after a former Air Force employee had notified about it in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nrk.no/nordland/kebnekaise-flyet-floy-med-feil-kart-1.14485005|title=Kebnekaise-flyet fl\u00f8y med feil kart (Norwegian)|last=Skj\u00e5stad Lysvold|first=Susanne|date=22 March 2019|work=NRK}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.klassekampen.no/article/20190322/ARTICLE/190329989|title=Gransker ulykken p\u00e5 nytt (Norwegian)|last=Lysberg|first=Magnus|date=22 March 2019|work=Klassekampen|last2=Tallaksen|first2=Simen}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in 2012}}\n{{Portal bar|Aviation|Norway|Sweden}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Norwegian Air Force C-130 crash, 2012}}\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 2012]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents involving controlled flight into terrain]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents caused by pilot error]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents caused by air traffic controller error]]\n[[Category:2012 in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving the Lockheed Hercules]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving Royal Norwegian Air Force aircraft]]\n[[Category:Kebnekaise]]\n[[Category:March 2012 events in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Why can't I edit Userpedia?", "label": "safe", "comment": "ATC played a role/factor in this accident.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2012_Norwegian_Air_Force_C-130_crash"}
